The sample was deep in 230 ml of 0.5 M HCl with 0.1–0.5% inhibitor solution concentration at temperatures of 313, 323 and 333 K for three hours to examine the impact of temperature on corrosion rate. A thermostat assembly with a precision of ±0.5 °C was employed to determine the temperature effect study. Thermostatic control within ±1 °C is often regarded as adequate, according to Wesley [25] and ASTM [26]. Triplicate experiments were done in each case and the mean value of the mass loss data were presented in mg.dm−2. Tables 2 and 3 show the results of calculations to find the activation energy (Ea), the free energy of adsorption (ΔG0 ads), inhibition efficiency (
η %
), and heat of adsorption (Qads).


   Weight loss process:
 The inhibition efficacy of the ELE rises with inhibitor concentration in 0.5 M HCl (Fig. 1), and the corrosion loss was reported to be decreasing order observed with increasing inhibitor concentration for 24 h at room temperature (303 K) and presented in mg.dm−2 (Fig. 2
).

The equilibrium constant for adsorption, K, and the falsehood values, n, is given in Eqs. (7) and (8), where n is a number between 0 and 1. Fig. 4
                         displays a straight-line plot of Log (θ) vs. Log (C) with an intercept of Log K, indicating that the experimental values suitable for the Freundlich model and demonstrating the adsorption of ELE on the Al surface follows this isotherm. Plotting Cinh/θ and Cinh also generated a straight line, confirming that inhibitors adsorb as per the Langmuir adsorption isotherm (Fig. 5
                        ).
